No. You should not aspirate before giving any vaccine, including COVID-19 vaccines. Aspiration can increase pain because of the combined effects of a longer needle-dwelling time in the tissues and shearing action (wiggling) of the needle. A discussion of vaccine administration best practices can be found in the ‚ÄúVaccine Administration‚Äù chapter of Epidemiology and Prevention of Vaccine-Preventable Diseases (Pink Book).


https://www.cdc.gov/vaccines/pubs/pinkbook/vac-admin.html
Inject Vaccines Rapidly Without Aspiration


Aspiration is not recommended before administering a vaccine. Aspiration prior to injection and injecting medication slowly are practices that have not been evaluated scientifically. Aspiration was originally recommended for theoretical safety reasons and injecting medication slowly was thought to decrease pain from sudden distention of muscle tissue. Aspiration can increase pain because of the combined effects of a longer needle-dwelling time in the tissues and shearing action (wiggling) of the needle. There are no reports of any person being injured because of failure to aspirate.

The veins and arteries within reach of a needle in the anatomic areas recommended for vaccination are too small to allow an intravenous push of vaccine without blowing out the vessel. A 2007 study from Canada compared infants‚Äô pain response using slow injection, aspiration, and slow withdrawal with another group using rapid injection, no aspiration, and rapid withdrawal. Based on behavioral and visual pain scales, the group that received the vaccine rapidly without aspiration experienced less pain. No immediate adverse events were reported with either injection technique.

As for not being held accountable that isn‚Äôt new either.  When most drugs cause harm, the pharmaceutical companies that make them can be sued in product liability lawsuits. But that isn't the case with vaccines. In 1986, Congress passed a law that protects vaccine manufacturers from being sued in civil personal injury and wrongful death lawsuits resulting from vaccine injuries.

Both drugmakers and federal government officials admit that although vaccines are created with the purpose of keeping the public safe, they can cause rare but serious, and sometimes fatal, side effects.

In the 1970s and 80s, drugmakers paid out millions to plaintiffs in hundreds of vaccine-related injury lawsuits. The litigation was complex and expensive because of how difficult it is to show epidemiological cause and effect in these cases.

Eventually, some drugmakers decided to stop making vaccines altogether. This drew alarm from public health officials, who worried about sustaining existing vaccines and also the development of new vaccines.

The National Childhood Vaccine Injury Act

Congress stepped in with the National Childhood Vaccine Injury Act of 1986 (the Vaccine Act) as a way to ensure that the injured would receive compensation, but also to protect drugmakers from open-ended liability.

In 2011, an important United States Supreme Court ruling clarified the type of lawsuits vaccine manufacturers are protected from under the Vaccine Act. In a 6-2 decision, the Court ruled that the federal law protects drugmakers from design-defect claims as long as the vaccine was properly manufactured and carried adequate warnings labels

Just wanted to say this for people who are experiencing heart palpitations. I've had SVT for over 10 years, started to get really bad over the last 3 years, just before I was diagnosed with it. Only in the last year have I discovered what stops these episodes as soon as they start (at least for me, it may not work for everyone.) Lay flat on your back, wrap your arms under your left thigh and bring your knee tightly up to you chest. Take a couple of deep breaths. You may need to repeat it once or twice. Data of this significance needs thorough review of the content and the tables together. The context was severely lacking months video, and apart from looking at basic patterns in the datasets, many data gaps or data quality gaps have been overlooked or not discussed.

Here are some of the data gaps and omissions with the current data:

1. Age groups data of trial group is vague. What only 2 age brackets when we know 10 year agile intervals tell a very different story. We know that a large amount of people under 55 don't actually show any symptoms. 
2. Where abouts in the countries were  the trial participants. We're they all from the same country or region within each country or were they spread all over the country? Seems pedantic, but in Australia, we might have 600 confirmed new cases in Victoria and 0 in Queensland. Because the participants were not all exposed to covid19, we don't know how much covid was spreading in which communities at the time of the trial.  
3. The statement says that the vaccine has 95% efficacy against symptomatic covid but we don't know how many people developed symptoms and returned a negative result within the first 4 days of the onset of symptoms. Were all people who reported adverse events forbthe vaccine tested for covid given the symptoms are the same?
4. The grouping of positive symptomatic covid is at intervals to suit the results and not standard intervals. 
E.g. after dose 1 and before dose 2 is a period of 3 weeks. Because covid can take up to 2 weeks to show symptoms, a larger number is shown. Then the interval moves to 0-7days after dose 2...Because covid symptoms can take up to 14 days to appear, there will be far fewer people showing symptoms in this period. There may have also been people in the trial who caught covid just before the trial started which will created a higher case rate after the first injection.
5. We don't know what % of people were considered as having covid symptoms and their symptoms were associated with the injection and they therefore were not tested for symptomatic covid. 
6. We don't know the COVID testing frequency of all trial participants and whether all participants were tested at the end of the trial with and without symptoms.  
7. Safety surveillance was only conducted for a subset of 8183 people.
The 8183 contains the adverse events of 1 or 2 injections and may have been the vaccine or the placebo. If all groups were equally split, we are looking at the adverse events of 2046 participants who had both doses of the vaccine. In saying that. In saying that, a maximum of 83% of diaries were completed each day. We don't know if it was the same people or there are gaps in data. 
8. What happened to Germany and Turkey trial participants?
9. In the follow up of adverse events, only 50% of trial participants (approx. 19000 participants), but we don't know the % of patients that were given the placebo vs. given the vaccine. Even less were followed up for 14 weeks and but we don't know which subset they were and how many people were included. . 
 10. Where did South Africa participants go? We started with 6 countries at the start of the trial, and it dropped down to 3. 
11. What was the 'no longer eligible' criteria between shot 1 and shot 2. 
12. 46 people had adverse events from shot 1 and didnt progress with the trial...what were those adverse events and what was the severity and health outcomes of those 46 people?
13. Adverse events were only solicited  for 8183 participants for 7 days after each dose and unsolicited feedback from patients who reported to them. A smaller subset was tracked for 14 weeks for efficacy but we don't know how many people and their demographics. 
14. 100 x 12-15 year olds were added in to calculate the person time years but were not part of the trial results. 
15. 196 participants who were HIV positive were eligible to take part in the trial, but their adverse events are excluded from the trial. We don't know how many completed the trial or whether any of them were part of the reactogenicity group who had to report their adverse events daily for 7 days post each injection. 
16. South Africa made the date cutoff and was part of the main safety group, but is not represented in the efficacy after 7 days and showing no symptoms of covid. So...how many of the South African participants had HIV and have been omitted from the finding, how many withdrew after 1 or 2 injections, or hiw many contracted symptomatic covid?

These are just some of the data gaps in the initial trial data. I hope we get more complete data soon.
